    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1862-03-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1862-03-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="662"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d662">
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                        Pruyn</persName>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 10.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State,</hi>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington,</hi>
                        </placeName>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1862-03-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">March</hi> 24, 1862.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> Mr. Harris’s despatch of November 23 (No. 49) has
                    been received. The views expressed therein concerning the questions between this
                    government and that of Japan, which had previously been committed to him for
                    consideration, <pb facs="0891" n="821" xml:id="pg_821"/> appear to the President
                    to be eminently sagacious. You will communicate these sentiments to Mr. Harris
                    if he shall yet be remaining at Yedo.</p>
                <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert H. Pruyn,</hi> Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c.,
                            &amp;c., &amp;c., Yedo.</hi>
                    </p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
